# Challenge 0 (Task2): Create Sample Project

[< Previous Challenge](./Challenge-00Task1.md) - **[Home](../README.md)** - [Next Challenge >](./Challenge-01.md)

## Introduction

This challenge is to create a sample project that contains three main resources, Azure AD group, Function App and Azure SQL. These resources will be used in later challenges of this event.

## Description

- Create a new Azure AD group using Cloud Self-Service Portal (Cloud SSP)
  1. Continue to Cloud-only Groups Management ([here][Cloud SSP Cloud Group])
  ![Cloud Self-Service Portal](Images/CloudSSP.png 'Cloud SSP')
  2. Click on the "+ New Azure AD Group" button
  ![Creating new Azure AD Group](Images/NewAzureADGroup.png 'New Azure AD Group')
  3. Set "\<Your Name\>-Cloudhack-ADGroup" as the display name and continue to create the group
  4. Login to the [Azure Portal] and verify that your AD group has been created

- Create a new Function App
  1. Create a new Function App using the following properties (those that are not specified below can be left as is):
      - Basics:
        - Subscription: \<Event Subscription\>
        - Resource Group: \<Your Resource Group\>
        - Function App name: \<Your Name\>-cloudhack-fa
        - Runtime stack: PowerShell Core
        - Version: 7.2
        - Region: `<any location>`
        - Operating System: Windows
        - Hosting options and plans: Functions Premiums
            - Create new plan with the name \<Your Name\>-cloudhack-asp and set the plan to Elastic Premium (EP1)
      - Storage:
        - Storage account: Create new storage account
      - Networking:
        - Enable public access: On
      - Monitoring
        - Enable Application Insights: Yes
        - Application Insights: Create new Application Insights in the same region as the Function App and choose the Log Analytics Workspace you created earlier as the Workspace
  2. In the "Review + create" tab, verify that your Function App looks like the one below
  ![Creating new Function App](Images/CreateFunctionApp.png 'Create Function App')
  3. Continue to create the Function App
  4. After the Function App and additional resources are successfully deployed, open Advanced Tools (under Development Tools menu) of the Function App and open PowerShell under Debug console in the menu bar
  ![Function App PowerShell debug console](Images/FAPowerShellConsole.png 'Function App PowerShell Debug Console')
  5. Navigate the PowerShell console to `C:\home\site\wwwroot` and edit the file `requirements.psd1`. Add the following requirements so that the file looks like to one below:
      - 'Az.Accounts' = '2.*'
      - 'SqlServer' = '22.*'
  ![Function App Requirements Module](Images/FARequirements.png 'Function App Requirements File')
  6. Go to diagnostics settings of the Function App and add a new diagnostic setting
  ![Function App diagnostic settings](Images/FADiagnosticsSetting.png 'Function App Diagnostic Settings')
  7. Check both boxes on the left column to send both Function Application Logs and Metrics. Check the box on the right column to send to Log Analytics workspace and choose the Log Analytics Workspace you created earlier. Diagnostic setting name is `<your name>fatola`.
  ![Adding new diagnostic setting to the Function App](Images/FAAddDiagnosticSetting.png 'Function App Add Diagnostic Setting')
  8. Enable system assigned identity for the Function App
  ![Enabling Function App Identity](Images/FAIdentity.png 'Enable Function App Identity')
  9. Add the object (managed identity) ID of the Function App to the Azure AD group you created earlier
  10. ***Restart*** the Function App and wait for it to finish before continuing

- Create new Functions for the Function App
  1. Create a new Function called "PrepareDB" using the HTTP trigger as the template.
  ![Creating PrepareDB function](Images/CreatePrepareDBFunction.png 'Create PrepareDB Function')
  2. Replace the code in the Function with the code from [PrepareDB.ps1](Sourcecode/PrepareDB.ps1)

  ```powershell

  using namespace System.Net

  # Input bindings are passed in via param block.
  param($Request, $TriggerMetadata)

  # Write to the Azure Functions log stream.
  Write-Host "PrepareDB function triggered, preparing database..."

  # Interact with query parameters or the body of the request.
  $DatabaseServerInstance = $Request.Query.Instance
  If (-not $DatabaseServerInstance) {
      $DatabaseServerInstance = $Request.Body.Instance
  }
  $DatabaseName = $Request.Query.DatabaseName
  If (-not $DatabaseName) {
      $DatabaseName = $Request.Body.DatabaseName
  }

  If ([string]::IsNullOrEmpty($DatabaseServerInstance) -or ([string]::IsNullOrEmpty($DatabaseName))) {
      $Response = "Invalid Database Instance and/or Name, please pass both of them in the query string or in the request body."
      Write-Host $Response
  }
  Else {
      Write-Host "Database Server Instance: $($DatabaseServerInstance)"
      Write-Host "Database Name: $($DatabaseName)"

      Connect-AzAccount -Identity
      If (-not ($DatabaseAccessToken = (Get-AzAccessToken -ResourceUrl https://database.windows.net).Token)) {
          $Response = "Invalid Database Access Token"
          Throw "Invalid Database token"
      }

      Write-Host "Dropping SampleTable if exists..."
      $Query = "IF  EXISTS (SELECT * FROM sys.objects WHERE object_id = OBJECT_ID(N'[dbo].[SampleTable]') AND type in (N'U')) DROP TABLE [dbo].[SampleTable]"
      Invoke-Sqlcmd -ServerInstance $DatabaseServerInstance -Database $DatabaseName -AccessToken $DatabaseAccessToken -Query $Query

      Write-Host "Creating a new SampleTable..."
      $Query = "CREATE TABLE [dbo].[SampleTable]([ID] [bigint] IDENTITY(1,1) NOT NULL, [Message] [nvarchar](max) NOT NULL, CONSTRAINT [PK_SampleTable] PRIMARY KEY CLUSTERED ([ID] ASC)WITH (STATISTICS_NORECOMPUTE = OFF, IGNORE_DUP_KEY = OFF, OPTIMIZE_FOR_SEQUENTIAL_KEY = OFF) ON [PRIMARY]) ON [PRIMARY] TEXTIMAGE_ON [PRIMARY]"
      Invoke-Sqlcmd -ServerInstance $DatabaseServerInstance -Database $DatabaseName -AccessToken $DatabaseAccessToken -Query $Query

      Write-Host "Populating SampleTable with 300 rows of data"
      $Query = "Declare @ID int Set @ID = 1 While @ID < 301 Begin INSERT INTO SampleTable VALUES ('Sample Data inserted by PrepareDB function, Row Number ' + CAST(@ID as nvarchar(10)) + 'Ridiculously Long Text: ') Print @ID Set @ID = @ID + 1 End"
      Invoke-Sqlcmd -ServerInstance $DatabaseServerInstance -Database $DatabaseName -AccessToken $DatabaseAccessToken -Query $Query

      $Response = "PrepareDB function successfully executed."
    Write-Host $Response
  }

  # Associate values to output bindings by calling 'Push-OutputBinding'.
  Push-OutputBinding -Name Response -Value ([HttpResponseContext]@{
      StatusCode = [HttpStatusCode]::OK
      Body = $Response
  })

  ```

  3. Create another Function called "GenerateErrorResponse" using the HTTP trigger as the template
  4. Replace the code in the Function with the code from [GenerateErrorResponse.ps1](Sourcecode/GenerateErrorResponse.ps1)

  ```powershell

  using namespace System.Net

  # Input bindings are passed in via param block.
  param($Request, $TriggerMetadata)

  # Write to the Azure Functions log stream.
  Write-Host "PowerShell HTTP trigger function processed a request."

  # Interact with query parameters or the body of the request.
  $StatusCode = $Request.Query.StatusCode
  if (-not $StatusCode) {
      $StatusCode = $Request.Body.StatusCode
  }

  If ([string]::IsNullOrEmpty($StatusCode)) {
      Write-Host "No Status Code received, using default value of 404"
      $StatusCode = 404
  }
  Else {
      Write-Host "Status Code: $($StatusCode)"
  }

  Write-Host "A list of valid Status Code can be found at https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.net.httpstatuscode?view=net-7.0"

  # Associate values to output bindings by calling 'Push-OutputBinding'.
  Push-OutputBinding -Name Response -Value ([HttpResponseContext]@{
      StatusCode = $StatusCode
  })

  ```

- Create a new Azure SQL
  1. Create a new Azure SQL choosing SQL databases as the plan and Single database as the resource type
  ![Creating new Azure SQL](Images/CreateAzureSQL.png 'Create Azure SQL')
  2. Continue to create Azure SQL using the following properties (those that are not specified below can be left as is):
      - Basics:
        - Subscription: \<Event Subscription\>
        - Resource Group: \<Your Resource Group\>
        - Database name: \<Your Name\>-cloudhack-sql
        - Server: Create new server
          - Server name: \<Your Name\>-cloudhack-sql-server
          - Location: `<any location>`
          - Authentication method: Use only Azure Active Directory (Azure AD) authentication
          - Set Azure AD admin: Choose the Azure AD group you created earlier
        - Compute + storage: Configure database with the following options:
          - Service tier: Basic (For less demanding workloads)
          - Data max size (GB): 0.1
        - Backup storage redundancy: Locally-redundant backup storage
      - Networking:
        - Connectivity method: Public endpoint
        - Allow Azure services and resources to access this server: Yes
        - Add current client IP address: No
  3. In the "Review + create" tab, verify that your Azure SQL looks like the one below
  ![Creating Azure SQL Database](Images/CreateAzureSQLDatabase.png 'Create Azure SQL Database')
  4. Continue to create the Azure SQL
  5. After the SQL database and additional resources are successfully deployed, go to diagnostics settings of the SQL database and add a new diagnostic setting
  ![SQL database diagnostic settings](Images/SQLDiagnosticsSetting.png 'SQL Database Diagnostic Settings')
  6. Check every boxes on the left column to send all logs, audit, and all metrics. Check the box on the right column to send to Log Analytics workspace and choose the Log Analytics Workspace you created earlier. Diagnostic setting name is `<your name>sqltola`.
  ![Adding new diagnostic setting to the SQL database](Images/SQLAddDiagnosticSetting.png 'SQL Database Add Diagnostic Setting')

## Success Criteria

- AD group is successfully created and contains at least 2 members:
  - Yourself
  - Identity of the Function App

- Function App and the associated Application Insights are successfully deployed and sending logs to your Log Analytics Workspace. The Function App must have the following Functions:
  - PrepareDB (HTTP Trigger)
  - GenerateErrorResponse (HTTP Trigger)

- Azure SQL and its Server are successfully deployed and sending logs to your Log Analytics Workspace.
